[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] According to frequentist inference, a **confidence interval** (**CI**) is a range of values which is likely to contain (in repeated sampling) the true value of an unknown statistical parameter, such as a population mean.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Rather than reporting a single point estimate (e.g.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] "the average screen time is 3 hours per day"), a confidence interval provides a range, such as 2 to 4 hours, along with a specified **confidence level**, typically 95%.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] A 95% confidence level does not imply a 95% probability that the true parameter lies within a particular calculated interval, which is instead associated with the credible interval in Bayesian inference.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] The confidence level instead reflects the long-run reliability of the method used to generate the interval.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] In other words, if the same sampling procedure were repeated 100 times from the same population, approximately 95 of the resulting intervals would be expected to contain the true population mean.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] The frequentist approach sees the true population mean as a fixed unknown constant, while the confidence interval is calculated using data from a random sample.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Because the sample is random, the interval endpoints are random variables.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Let X be a random sample from a probability distribution with statistical parameter $(\theta ,\varphi )$ .
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Here, $\theta$ is the quantity to be estimated, while $\varphi$ includes other parameters (if any) that determine the distribution.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] The number $\gamma$ , which is typically large (e.g.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] 0.95), is sometimes given in the form $1-\alpha$ (or as a percentage $100\%\cdot (1-\alpha )$ ), where $\alpha$ is a small positive number, often 0.05.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] It means that the interval ${\textstyle (u(X),v(X))}$ has a probability ${\textstyle \gamma }$ of covering the value of ${\textstyle \theta }$ in repeated sampling.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] In many applications, confidence intervals that have exactly the required confidence level are hard to construct, but approximate intervals can be computed.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] to an acceptable level of approximation.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] $P(u(X)<\theta <v(X))\geq \ \gamma$ When it is known that the coverage probability can be strictly larger than $\gamma$ for some parameter values, the confidence interval is called conservative, i.e., it errs on the safe side; which also means that the interval can be wider than need be.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] There are many ways of calculating confidence intervals, and the best method depends on the situation.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Two widely applicable methods are bootstrapping and the central limit theorem.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] where ${\textstyle \mu }$ and n are the population mean and the sample size, respectively.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] has a Student's *t* distribution with ${\textstyle n-1}$ degrees of freedom.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] This value is useful because its distribution does not depend on the values of the unobservable parameters ${\textstyle \mu }$ and ${\textstyle \sigma ^{2}}$ ; i.e., it is a pivotal quantity.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Suppose we wanted to calculate a 95% confidence interval for ${\textstyle \mu .}$ First, let ${\textstyle c}$ be the 97.5th percentile of the distribution of ${\textstyle T}$ .
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Then there is a 2.5% chance that ${\textstyle T}$ will be less than ${\textstyle -c}$ and a 2.5% chance that it will be larger than ${\textstyle +c}$ (as the *t* distribution is symmetric about 0).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] where $P_{X}$ is the probability measure for the sample $X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}$ .
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] It means that there is 95% probability with which this condition ${\bar {X}}-{\frac {cS}{\sqrt {n}}}\leq \mu \leq {\bar {X}}+{\frac {cS}{\sqrt {n}}}$ occurs in repeated sampling.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] After observing a sample, we find values ${\bar {x}}$ for ${\bar {X}}$ and s for $S,$ from which we compute the below interval, and we say it is a 95% confidence interval for the mean.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Various interpretations of a confidence interval can be given (taking the 95% confidence interval as an example in the following).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Confidence intervals and levels are frequently misunderstood, and published studies have shown that even professional scientists often misinterpret them.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] For example, suppose a factory produces metal rods, and a random sample of 25 rods gives a 95% confidence interval of 36.8 to 39.0 mm for the population mean length.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Instead, the 95% confidence level means that if we took 100 such samples, we would expect the true population mean to lie within approximately 95 of the calculated intervals.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Interpreting confidence intervals is especially tricky when multiple groups are involved.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Two common misconceptions are: that two groups are significantly different if their CIs "just touch," and that they differ when one group's CI excludes the other's mean.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Neither of these is true in general, but even experienced researchers often make these mistakes.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] A confidence interval is used to estimate a population parameter, such as the mean.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] For example, the expected value of a fair six-sided die is 3.5.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Based on repeated sampling, after computing many 95% confidence intervals, roughly 95% of them will contain 3.5 (and the width of the confidence interval shrinks with sample size).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] A prediction interval, on the other hand, provides a range within which a future individual observation is expected to fall with a certain probability.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] In the case of a single roll of a fair six-sided die, an exact 95% prediction interval does not exist.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] However, there are exact 95% prediction intervals for rolling a twenty-sided die.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] One such interval is $[1,19]$ , since 95% of the time the roll will result in a 19 or less, and the remaining 5% will result in a 20.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] The key distinction is that confidence intervals quantify uncertainty in estimating parameters, while prediction intervals quantify uncertainty in forecasting future observations.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] In many common settings, such as estimating the mean of a normal distribution with known variance, confidence intervals coincide with credible intervals under non-informative priors.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] In such cases, common misconceptions about confidence intervals (e.g. interpreting them as probability statements about the parameter) may yield practically correct conclusions.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Welch presented an example which clearly shows the difference between the theory of confidence intervals and other theories of interval estimation (including Fisher's fiducial intervals and objective Bayesian intervals).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Robinson called this example "[p]ossibly the best known counterexample for Neyman's version of confidence interval theory." To Welch, it showed the superiority of confidence interval theory; to critics of the theory, it shows a deficiency.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Suppose that $X_{1},X_{2}$ are independent observations from a uniform $(\theta -1/2,\theta +1/2)$ distribution.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] A fiducial or objective Bayesian argument can be used to derive the interval estimate ${\bar {X}}\pm {\frac {1-|X_{1}-X_{2}|}{4}},$ which is also a 50% confidence procedure.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] The average width of the intervals from the first procedure is less than that of the second.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Hence, the first procedure is preferred under classical confidence interval theory.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] However, when $|X_{1}-X_{2}|\geq 1/2$ , intervals from the first procedure are *guaranteed* to contain the true value $\theta$ : Therefore, the nominal 50% confidence coefficient is unrelated to the uncertainty we should have that a specific interval contains the true value.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] The second procedure does not have this property.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Moreover, when the first procedure generates a very short interval, this indicates that $X_{1},X_{2}$ are very close together and hence only offer the information in a single data point.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Yet the first interval will exclude almost all reasonable values of the parameter due to its short width.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] The two counter-intuitive properties of the first procedure – 100% coverage when $X_{1},X_{2}$ are far apart and almost 0% coverage when $X_{1},X_{2}$ are close together – balance out to yield 50% coverage on average.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] However, despite the first procedure being optimal, its intervals offer neither an assessment of the precision of the estimate nor an assessment of the uncertainty one should have that the interval contains the true value.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] This example is used to argue against naïve interpretations of confidence intervals.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] If a confidence procedure is asserted to have properties beyond that of the nominal coverage (such as relation to precision, or a relationship with Bayesian inference), those properties must be proved; they do not follow from the fact that a procedure is a confidence procedure.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Steiger suggested a number of confidence procedures for common effect size measures in ANOVA.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] This behavior is consistent with the relationship between the confidence procedure and significance testing: as *F* becomes so small that the group means are much closer together than we would expect by chance, a significance test might indicate rejection for most or all values of *ω*2.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Hence the interval will be very narrow or even empty (or, by a convention suggested by Steiger, containing only 0).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] However, this does *not* indicate that the estimate of *ω*2 is very precise.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] In a sense, it indicates the opposite: that the trustworthiness of the results themselves may be in doubt.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] This is contrary to the common interpretation of confidence intervals that they reveal the precision of the estimate.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] Methods for calculating confidence intervals for the binomial proportion appeared from the 1920s.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] The main ideas of confidence intervals in general were developed in the early 1930s, and the first thorough and general account was given by Jerzy Neyman in 1937.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] In medical journals, confidence intervals were promoted in the 1970s but only became widely used in the 1980s.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/confidence-interval] By 1988, medical journals were requiring the reporting of confidence intervals.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] drawn from that distribution, and the horizontal steps of the blue step function (including the leftmost point in each step but not including the rightmost point) form the empirical distribution function of that sample.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] In statistics, an **empirical distribution function** (a.k.a. an **empirical cumulative distribution function**, **eCDF**) is the distribution function associated with the empirical measure of a sample.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] This cumulative distribution function is a step function that jumps up by 1/*n* at each of the *n* data points.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] Its value at any specified value of the measured variable is the fraction of observations of the measured variable that are less than or equal to the specified value.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] The empirical distribution function is an estimate of the cumulative distribution function that generated the points in the sample.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] It converges with probability 1 to that underlying distribution, according to the Glivenko–Cantelli theorem.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] A number of results exist to quantify the rate of convergence of the empirical distribution function to the underlying cumulative distribution function.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] A simple empirical estimate is the frequency distribution.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] Let (*X*1, …, *X**n*) be independent, identically distributed real random variables with the common cumulative distribution function *F*(*t*).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] For a fixed *t*, the indicator $\mathbf {1} _{X_{i}\leq t}$ is a Bernoulli random variable with parameter *p* = *F*(*t*); hence $n{\widehat {F}}_{n}(t)$ is a binomial random variable with mean *nF*(*t*) and variance *nF*(*t*)(1 − *F*(*t*)).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] This implies that ${\widehat {F}}_{n}(t)$ is an unbiased estimator for *F*(*t*).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] In some textbooks, the empirical distribution function is defined as ${\widehat {F}}_{n}(t)={\frac {1}{n+1}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}\mathbf {1} _{X_{i}\leq t}$ However, since the ratio (*n* + 1)/*n* approaches 1 as *n* goes to infinity, the asymptotic properties of the two definitions are the same.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] By the strong law of large numbers, the estimator ${\widehat {F}}_{n}(t)$ converges to *F*(*t*) as *n* → ∞ almost surely, for every value of *t*: ${\widehat {F}}_{n}(t)\ {\xrightarrow {\text{a.s.}}}\ F(t);$ thus the estimator ${\widehat {F}}_{n}(t)$ is consistent.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] This expression asserts the pointwise convergence of the empirical distribution function to the true cumulative distribution function.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] Other norm functions may be reasonably used here instead of the sup-norm.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] For example, the L2-norm gives rise to the Cramér–von Mises statistic.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] The asymptotic distribution can be further characterized in several different ways.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] Alternatively, the rate of convergence of ${\sqrt {n}}({\widehat {F}}_{n}-F)$ can also be quantified in terms of the asymptotic behavior of the sup-norm of this expression.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-distribution-function] As per the above bounds, we can plot the Empirical CDF, CDF and confidence intervals for different distributions by using any one of the statistical implementations.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] In probability theory and statistics, the **empirical probability** or **experimental probability** of an event is an estimate of the probability of the event occurring.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] A common estimator for the empirical probability is the relative frequency, calculated as the ratio of the number of recorded event outcomes to the total number of trials.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] It is produced by means not of a theoretical sample space but of an empirical sample.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] More generally, empirical probability may be estimated from experience and observation.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] Mathematically, given an event A in a sample space, the relative frequency of A is the ratio ⁠ ${\tfrac {m}{n}},$ ⁠ m being the number of outcomes in which the event A occurs, and n being the total number of outcomes of the experiment.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] In simple cases, where the result of a trial only determines whether or not the specified event has occurred, modelling using a binomial distribution might be appropriate and then the empirical estimate is the maximum likelihood estimate.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] It is the Bayesian estimate for the same case if certain assumptions are made for the prior distribution of the probability.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] An advantage of estimating probabilities using empirical probabilities is that this procedure is relatively free of assumptions.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] 2. that they prefer strawberry jam to raspberry jam.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] A direct estimate could be found by counting the number of men who satisfy both conditions to give the empirical probability of the combined condition.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] An alternative estimate could be found by multiplying the proportion of men who are over 6 feet in height with the proportion of men who prefer strawberry jam to raspberry jam, but this estimate relies on the assumption that the two conditions are statistically independent.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] A disadvantage in using empirical probabilities arises in estimating probabilities which are either very close to zero, or very close to one.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] In these cases very large sample sizes would be needed in order to estimate such probabilities to a good standard of relative accuracy.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] Here statistical models can help, depending on the context, and in general one can hope that such models would provide improvements in accuracy compared to empirical probabilities, provided that the assumptions involved actually do hold.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] For example, consider estimating the probability that the lowest of the daily-maximum temperatures at a site in February in any one year is less than zero degrees Celsius.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] A record of such temperatures in past years could be used to estimate this probability.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] A model-based alternative would be to select a family of probability distributions and fit it to the dataset containing past years′ values.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] The fitted distribution would provide an alternative estimate of the desired probability.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] This alternative method can provide an estimate of the probability even if all values in the record are greater than zero.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] The phrase *a-posteriori probability* is also used as an alternative to "empirical probability" or "relative frequency".
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] The use of the phrase "a-posteriori" is reminiscent of terms in Bayesian statistics, but is not directly related to Bayesian inference, where *a-posteriori probability* is occasionally used to refer to posterior probability, which is different even though it has a confusingly similar name.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/empirical-probability] The term *a-posteriori probability*, in its meaning suggestive of "empirical probability", may be used in conjunction with *a priori probability* which represents an estimate of a probability not based on any observations, but based on deductive reasoning.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] In statistics, **resampling** is the creation of new samples based on one observed sample.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Permutation tests rely on resampling the original data assuming the null hypothesis.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Based on the resampled data it can be concluded how likely the original data is to occur under the null hypothesis.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] It has been called the **plug-in principle**, as it is the method of estimation of functionals of a population distribution by evaluating the same functionals at the empirical distribution based on a sample.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] For example, when estimating the population mean, this method uses the sample mean; to estimate the population median, it uses the sample median; to estimate the population regression line, it uses the sample regression line.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] It may also be used for constructing hypothesis tests.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] It is often used as a robust alternative to inference based on parametric assumptions when those assumptions are in doubt, or where parametric inference is impossible or requires very complicated formulas for the calculation of standard errors.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Bootstrapping techniques are also used in the updating-selection transitions of particle filters, genetic type algorithms and related resample/reconfiguration Monte Carlo methods used in computational physics.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] In this context, the bootstrap is used to replace sequentially empirical weighted probability measures by empirical measures.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] The bootstrap allows to replace the samples with low weights by copies of the samples with high weights.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Cross-validation is a statistical method for validating a predictive model.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Subsets of the data are held out for use as validating sets; a model is fit to the remaining data (a training set) and used to predict for the validation set.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Averaging the quality of the predictions across the validation sets yields an overall measure of prediction accuracy.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Cross-validation is employed repeatedly in building decision trees.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] One form of cross-validation leaves out a single observation at a time; this is similar to the jackknife.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Another, *K*-fold cross-validation, splits the data into *K* subsets; each is held out in turn as the validation set.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] For comparison, in regression analysis methods such as linear regression, each *y* value draws the regression line toward itself, making the prediction of that value appear more accurate than it really is.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Cross-validation applied to linear regression predicts the *y* value for each observation without using that observation.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] This is often used for deciding how many predictor variables to use in regression.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Without cross-validation, adding predictors always reduces the residual sum of squares (or possibly leaves it unchanged).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] In contrast, the cross-validated mean-square error will tend to decrease if valuable predictors are added, but increase if worthless predictors are added.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Subsampling is an alternative method for approximating the sampling distribution of an estimator.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] 2. resampling is done without replacement.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] The advantage of subsampling is that it is valid under much weaker conditions compared to the bootstrap.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] In particular, a set of sufficient conditions is that the rate of convergence of the estimator is known and that the limiting distribution is continuous.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] In addition, the resample (or subsample) size must tend to infinity together with the sample size but at a smaller rate, so that their ratio converges to zero.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] While subsampling was originally proposed for the case of independent and identically distributed (iid) data only, the methodology has been extended to cover time series data as well; in this case, one resamples blocks of subsequent data rather than individual data points.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] There are many cases of applied interest where subsampling leads to valid inference whereas bootstrapping does not; for example, such cases include examples where the rate of convergence of the estimator is not the square root of the sample size or when the limiting distribution is non-normal.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] When both subsampling and the bootstrap are consistent, the bootstrap is typically more accurate.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] RANSAC is a popular algorithm using subsampling.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Jackknifing (jackknife cross-validation), is used in statistical inference to estimate the bias and standard error (variance) of a statistic, when a random sample of observations is used to calculate it.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Historically, this method preceded the invention of the bootstrap with Quenouille inventing this method in 1949 and Tukey extending it in 1958.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] This method was foreshadowed by Mahalanobis who in 1946 suggested repeated estimates of the statistic of interest with half the sample chosen at random.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] He coined the name 'interpenetrating samples' for this method.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Quenouille invented this method with the intention of reducing the bias of the sample estimate.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] The basic idea behind the jackknife variance estimator lies in systematically recomputing the statistic estimate, leaving out one or more observations at a time from the sample set.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] From this new set of replicates of the statistic, an estimate for the bias and an estimate for the variance of the statistic can be calculated.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Jackknife is equivalent to the random (subsampling) leave-one-out cross-validation, it only differs in the goal.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] For many statistical parameters the jackknife estimate of variance tends asymptotically to the true value almost surely.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] In technical terms one says that the jackknife estimate is consistent.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] The jackknife is consistent for the sample means, sample variances, central and non-central t-statistics (with possibly non-normal populations), sample coefficient of variation, maximum likelihood estimators, least squares estimators, correlation coefficients and regression coefficients.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] It is not consistent for the sample median.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] In the case of a unimodal variate the ratio of the jackknife variance to the sample variance tends to be distributed as one half the square of a chi square distribution with two degrees of freedom.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Instead of using the jackknife to estimate the variance, it may instead be applied to the log of the variance.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] This transformation may result in better estimates particularly when the distribution of the variance itself may be non normal.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] The jackknife, like the original bootstrap, is dependent on the independence of the data.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Extensions of the jackknife to allow for dependence in the data have been proposed.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] One such extension is the delete-a-group method used in association with Poisson sampling.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Both methods, the bootstrap and the jackknife, estimate the variability of a statistic from the variability of that statistic between subsamples, rather than from parametric assumptions.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] For the more general jackknife, the delete-m observations jackknife, the bootstrap can be seen as a random approximation of it.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Both yield similar numerical results, which is why each can be seen as approximation to the other.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Although there are huge theoretical differences in their mathematical insights, the main practical difference for statistics users is that the bootstrap gives different results when repeated on the same data, whereas the jackknife gives exactly the same result each time.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Because of this, the jackknife is popular when the estimates need to be verified several times before publishing (e.g., official statistics agencies).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] On the other hand, when this verification feature is not crucial and it is of interest not to have a number but just an idea of its distribution, the bootstrap is preferred (e.g., studies in physics, economics, biological sciences).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Whether to use the bootstrap or the jackknife may depend more on operational aspects than on statistical concerns of a survey.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] The jackknife, originally used for bias reduction, is more of a specialized method and only estimates the variance of the point estimator.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] This can be enough for basic statistical inference (e.g., hypothesis testing, confidence intervals).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] The bootstrap, on the other hand, first estimates the whole distribution (of the point estimator) and then computes the variance from that.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] While powerful and easy, this can become highly computationally intensive.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] "The bootstrap can be applied to both variance and distribution estimation problems.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] However, the bootstrap variance estimator is not as good as the jackknife or the balanced repeated replication (BRR) variance estimator in terms of the empirical results.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Furthermore, the bootstrap variance estimator usually requires more computations than the jackknife or the BRR.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] There is a special consideration with the jackknife, particularly with the delete-1 observation jackknife.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] It should only be used with smooth, differentiable statistics (e.g., totals, means, proportions, ratios, odd ratios, regression coefficients, etc.; not with medians or quantiles).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] This could become a practical disadvantage.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] This disadvantage is usually the argument favoring bootstrapping over jackknifing.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] More general jackknifes than the delete-1, such as the delete-m jackknife or the delete-all-but-2 Hodges–Lehmann estimator, overcome this problem for the medians and quantiles by relaxing the smoothness requirements for consistent variance estimation.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Usually the jackknife is easier to apply to complex sampling schemes than the bootstrap.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Complex sampling schemes may involve stratification, multiple stages (clustering), varying sampling weights (non-response adjustments, calibration, post-stratification) and under unequal-probability sampling designs.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] Theoretical aspects of both the bootstrap and the jackknife can be found in Shao and Tu (1995), whereas a basic introduction is accounted in Wolter (2007).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/resampling-statistics] The bootstrap estimate of model prediction bias is more precise than jackknife estimates with linear models such as linear discriminant function or multiple regression.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] The **standard error** (**SE**) of a statistic (usually an estimator of a parameter, like the average or mean) is the standard deviation of its sampling distribution.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] The standard error is often used in calculations of confidence intervals.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] The sampling distribution of a mean is generated by repeated sampling from the same population and recording the sample mean per sample.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] This forms a distribution of different sample means, and this distribution has its own mean and variance.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] Mathematically, the variance of the sampling mean distribution obtained is equal to the variance of the population divided by the sample size.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] This is because as the sample size increases, sample means cluster more closely around the population mean.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] Therefore, the relationship between the standard error of the mean and the standard deviation is such that, for a given sample size, the standard error of the mean equals the standard deviation divided by the square root of the sample size.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] In other words, the standard error of the mean is a measure of the dispersion of sample means around the population mean.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] In regression analysis, the term "standard error" refers either to the square root of the reduced chi-squared statistic or the standard error for a particular regression coefficient (as used in, say, confidence intervals).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] Suppose a statistically independent sample of n observations $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}$ is taken from a statistical population with a standard deviation of $\sigma$ (the standard deviation of the population).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] The standard deviation $\sigma$ of the population being sampled is seldom known.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] When the sample size is small, using the standard deviation of the sample instead of the true standard deviation of the population will tend to systematically underestimate the population standard deviation, and therefore also the standard error.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] With *n* = 2, the underestimate is about 25%, but for *n* = 6, the underestimate is only 5%.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] Gurland and Tripathi (1971) provide a correction and equation for this effect.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] Sokal and Rohlf (1981) give an equation of the correction factor for small samples of *n* < 20.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] See unbiased estimation of standard deviation for further discussion.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] The standard error on the mean may be derived from the variance of a sum of independent random variables, given the definition of variance and some properties thereof.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] where a propagation in variance is used in the 2nd equality.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] In other words, if there are a large number of observations per sampling ( ${\textstyle n}$ is high compared with the population variance ${\textstyle \sigma }$ ), then the calculated mean per sample ${\textstyle {\bar {x}}}$ is expected to be close to the population mean x .
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] For correlated random variables, the sample variance needs to be computed according to the Markov chain central limit theorem.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] There are cases when a sample is taken without knowing, in advance, how many observations will be acceptable according to some criterion.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] In such cases, the sample size N is a random variable whose variation adds to the variation of X such that, $\operatorname {Var} (T)=\operatorname {E} (N)\operatorname {Var} (X)+\operatorname {Var} (N){\big (}\operatorname {E} (X){\big )}^{2}$ which follows from the law of total variance.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] If N has a *Poisson distribution*, then $\operatorname {E} (N)=\operatorname {Var} (N)$ with estimator $n=N$ .
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] Hence the estimator of $\operatorname {Var} (T)$ becomes $nS_{X}^{2}+n{\bar {X}}^{2}$ , leading the following formula for standard error: $\operatorname {Standard~Error} ({\bar {X}})={\sqrt {\frac {S_{X}^{2}+{\bar {X}}^{2}}{n}}}$ (since the standard deviation is the square root of the variance).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] In many practical applications, the true value of *σ* is unknown.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] As a result, we need to use a distribution that takes into account that spread of possible *σ'*s.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] When the true underlying distribution is known to be Gaussian, although with unknown σ, then the resulting estimated distribution follows the Student t-distribution.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] The standard error is the standard deviation of the Student t-distribution.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] T-distributions are slightly different from Gaussian, and vary depending on the size of the sample.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] Small samples are somewhat more likely to underestimate the population standard deviation and have a mean that differs from the true population mean, and the Student t-distribution accounts for the probability of these events with somewhat heavier tails compared to a Gaussian.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] To estimate the standard error of a Student t-distribution it is sufficient to use the sample standard deviation "s" instead of *σ*, and we could use this value to calculate confidence intervals.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] An example of how $\operatorname {SE}$ (Standard Error) is used to make confidence intervals of the unknown population mean is shown.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] If the sampling distribution is normally distributed, the sample mean, the standard error, and the quantiles of the normal distribution can be used to calculate confidence intervals for the true population mean.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] In particular, the standard error of a sample statistic (such as sample mean) is the actual or estimated standard deviation of the sample mean in the process by which it was generated.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] In other words, it is the actual or estimated standard deviation of the sampling distribution of the sample statistic.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] The notation for standard error can be any one of SE, SEM (for standard error of *measurement* or *mean*), or SE.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] In scientific and technical literature, experimental data are often summarized either using the mean and standard deviation of the sample data or the mean with the standard error.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] This often leads to confusion about their interchangeability.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] However, the mean and standard deviation are descriptive statistics, whereas the standard error of the mean is descriptive of the random sampling process.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] The standard deviation of the sample data is a description of the variation in measurements, while the standard error of the mean is a probabilistic statement about how the sample size will provide a better bound on estimates of the population mean, in light of the central limit theorem.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] Put simply, the **standard error** of the sample mean is an estimate of how far the sample mean is likely to be from the population mean, whereas the **standard deviation** of the sample is the degree to which individuals within the sample differ from the sample mean.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] The formula given above for the standard error assumes that the population is infinite.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] Nonetheless, it is often used for finite populations when people are interested in measuring the process that created the existing finite population (this is called an analytic study).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] Though the above formula is not exactly correct when the population is finite, the difference between the finite- and infinite-population versions will be small when sampling fraction is small (e.g. a small proportion of a finite population is studied).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] In this case people often do not correct for the finite population, essentially treating it as an "approximately infinite" population.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] If one is interested in measuring an existing finite population that will not change over time, then it is necessary to adjust for the population size (called an enumerative study).
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] The effect of the FPC is that the error becomes zero when the sample size *n* is equal to the population size *N*.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] This happens in survey methodology when sampling without replacement.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] If sampling with replacement, then FPC does not come into play.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] This approximate formula is for moderate to large sample sizes; the reference gives the exact formulas for any sample size, and can be applied to heavily autocorrelated time series like Wall Street stock quotes.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] Moreover, this formula works for positive and negative ρ alike.
[src:bootstrap-resampling/standard-error] See also unbiased estimation of standard deviation for more discussion.
